This wine dataset consists of 13 features, with 4898 observations, and was created by: Paulo Cortez (Univ. Minho), Antonio Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida, Telmo Matos and Jose Reis in 2009. This dataset is a tidy dataset, and contains no missing values. The 13 features are: X, fixed.acidity,volatile. acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol and quality.The first column or feature X is index that can be removed from the original dataset.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 4898 observations of wine in this dataset with 12 features (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol and quality). Quality is the output attribute that we are interested in. All the features are numerical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature that I want to learn and predict is the quality. I would like to determine which features are best for predicting the quality of wine. I suspect density, alcohol,residual sugar and some combination of acidities can be used to build a predictive model to price diamonds.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Total sulfur dioxide and density likely contribute to wine quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Sum of all acidities is what I create so far. I may create some combinations later.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

  1. Quality has most values concentrated in the categories 5, 6 and 7. Only a small proportion is in the categories [3, 4] and [8, 9] and none in the categories [1, 2] and 10.

  2. There are outliers in Fixed acidity, volatile acidity and citric acid. I eliminated these outliers, and distribution of these variables seems to be more symmetric.

  3. Residual sugar has a right skewed distribution, and it remain right skewed after taking out outliers.

  4. Alcohol has an anormal distribution, but it does not have outliers.

Bivariate Plots Section

Pairwise plotting variables using ‘ggcorr’ function to get a general correlation sense of data.

Faceted all paired features to genarally learn relation of them.

For this data, the most interesting part is what determine the wine quality. So I ingnore some features which are not quite related with quality variable. The features I’m interested in are: residual.sugar, chlorides, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, alcohol and total.acidity.

Then I factor quality feature to boxplots with these related features. From this alcohol vs quality plot, wines with quality greater than 6 generally have higher alcohol content.

From this density vs quality plot, wines with quality greater than 6 generally have lower density. Since alcohol density is less than water, wines with more alcohol have lower density and higher quality.

From this residual suagr vs quality plot, it is hard to tell any relation in it. But the highest quality wine have the slightest residual residual sugar.

From this chlorides vs quality plot, it just have a little downward trend when quality inceasing.

From this total acidity vs quality plot, I couldn’t see any relation from this boxplot.

I couldn’t any relation from this boxplot. All the above boxplots are some how related to quality. Next, I will explore some other interesting features.

Residual sugar and density have 0.84 correlation. This is verified from this plot. I think this is because sugar solvent has higher density.

Also, a strong relationship between density and alcohol is verified. Their correlation is -0.78.

From alcohol and quality boxplot, I thought they should have a relation. So I made this scatter plot to verify it.

Also, I made this quanlity VS density scatter plot to verify my thought from their boxplot.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

I observed quality vs alcohol and quality vs density since quality is the main interest of this dataset. Alcohol has 0.44 correlation wieh quality while density has -0.31. But alcohol and density are somehow related because alcohol has smaller densidy than water.

For other features, I couldn’t any significant relations with quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Density generall has relation with all ingredients(acid, sugar, sodium).

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is between density and residual sugar(0.84). The second one is density with alcohol (-0.78) .

Description Three

Reflection

There are 4898 wines infomation in this wine dataset. Before I investigate this dataset, I managed to acquire some knowledge from internet to deeply understand these features in it.Basicly, Sweet Taste (sugars + alcohols) and Acid Taste(acids) determine the quality of wines.Then I create histogram for each feature to understand features. The main interest of this dataset is quality. I found several features might have relations with it: alcohol, sugar, density, acid,etc. The most interesting feature for me is alcohol. Then I focused on relations in main interest,alcohol and other features.

I found density almost has strong relation to all features. This is reasonable since all content in wines can affect density. I also found PH value is highly related with acid. The most interesting part I found is high quality wines tend to have high content of alcohol.

Then I built a linear model to predict. Unfortunately, the accuracy is not good enough. I will try to build some other regression model(e.g., support vector machine(SVM)) to enhance the accuracy.
